{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c97b5e06-c9e7-4360-9178-7550fce35d2e","content":"Here's the evaluation performance analysis for `EvalHeavy.csproj`:\n\n## Issues Found\n\n### 1. File I/O Property Function (High Impact)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nReading files via property functions during evaluation is **synchronous and blocking**. This runs on every evaluation (IDE design-time builds, restore, etc.). Move file reading to a target at execution time instead.\n\n### 2. Expensive Glob Pattern (Medium Impact)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\nThe `**\\*.*` glob walks the **entire directory tree** during evaluation. If the tree grows (e.g., `node_modules`, large generated folders), this becomes very costly. Narrow the glob to specific extensions or directories.\n\n### 3. Deep Import Chain (Low Impact — currently)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nThree levels of chained imports. Not critical at 3 levels, but this pattern scales poorly. If this grows past ~20 levels it noticeably slows evaluation. Keep it flat where possible.\n\n---\n\n**Recommendation priority:** Fix #1 (property function I/O) first — it's the most expensive per-evaluation cost. Then tighten the glob in #2.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8784b714-c950-4d0e-ac50-1251d540b466","outputTokens":346,"requestId":"F024:97105:1262F09:14E46DE:69F9452F"},"id":"f61f0b97-b73b-4927-9e4d-6f7217f0de1f","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:17:44.731Z","parentId":"efb278de-0f67-42c2-8182-4bde8f436d39"}
